== SPI streaming slave (raw)

A deliberately minimal SPI slave that exists for one purpose: pin
down the maximum SCLK frequency the iCE40-HX1K can sustain when
the wire protocol is stripped of every framing byte. The MP135
host drives a raw indirect read --- IMODE=0, ADMODE=0, no dummy
--- so every SCLK cycle inside CS-low carries useful payload.
The slave's job is to put the next byte of an incrementing
`A[7:0]` pattern on the bus, in lockstep with SCLK, with no
opcode latch, address capture, or dummy-cycle counter in the
critical path.

Two synthesis variants are produced from one source. `LANES=1`
drives the single-lane MISO line `io[1]` on `negedge sclk`,
MSB-first; the bench command on the host side is `b <len> 0 1`.
`LANES=4` drives all four lanes on `negedge sclk`; the bench
command is `b <len> 1 1`. The 4-lane case follows the convention
the rest of this codebase has settled on: the STM32MP1 QUADSPI
indirect-read engine assembles each byte as
`{second_sample, first_sample}`, so the FIRST negedge of a byte
cycle carries the LOWER nibble and the SECOND negedge carries
the UPPER. This matches the
`<<SPI: quad output negedge presenter>>` / nibble precompute in
the `qspi` chapter --- byte-swap-on-the-wire is a host-side
post-process there too.

Reset is asynchronous off `cs_n`: while CS is high (frame idle)
all sclk-domain state is held cleared, and the falling edge of
CS releases the reset cleanly before the master's first SCLK
rise. Mode 0 says SCLK idles low and the slave sets up data on
each negedge for the master to sample on the following posedge,
so the very first negedge of the data phase needs valid output
already in `q`. We get that by precomputing the nibble (or bit)
on the rising edge that immediately precedes the negedge and
registering the result one half-cycle later; the rise that
"completes" byte K-1 primes the negedge that opens byte K.

<<spi.v>>=
module spi #(
      parameter LANES = 1
   ) (
      input        cs_n,
      input        sclk,
      inout  [3:0] io
   );
   <<SPI streaming: state>>
   <<SPI streaming: sclk processes>>
   <<SPI streaming: io drivers>>
endmodule
@

The state lives in the sclk domain. `data_byte` is the running
pattern counter (advances at byte boundaries) and is shared
across both LANES variants. The `phase` counter and the output
register `q` are declared inside the active generate branch so
each variant carries only the bits it actually uses --- 3 bits
of phase plus 1 bit of `q` for 1-lane (eight rises per byte,
MSB-first), and 1 bit of phase plus 4 bits of `q` for 4-lane
(two rises per byte, lower nibble first then upper).

The presented output is a `negedge`-clocked register `q`,
declared inside whichever generate branch is active so the
4-lane case has a 4-bit register and the 1-lane case has a
single-bit register --- letting the linter see every bit
reach a pin.

<<SPI streaming: state>>=
reg [7:0] data_byte;
initial data_byte = 8'd0;
@

The posedge process advances `phase` and schedules the
byte-pattern increment at the rise that closes the current
byte. The negedge process registers the next slice of
`data_byte` onto `q`. `cs_n` is the asynchronous reset for
both. The "`data_byte` increment fires on the rise that ends
byte K" arrangement lets the negedge process drive byte K+1's
first slice immediately, without any extra prefetch register:
the negedge that follows sees the post-increment `data_byte`
directly.

For 4-lane the negedge picks the lower nibble when
`phase[0] == 0` and the upper nibble when `phase[0] == 1` ---
matching the STM32MP1 QUADSPI indirect-read assembly of
`{second_sample, first_sample}`. For 1-lane the negedge picks
bit `7 - phase`, MSB-first.

<<SPI streaming: sclk processes>>=
generate if (LANES == 4) begin : g_quad
   reg       phase;
   reg [3:0] q;
   initial begin phase = 1'b0; q = 4'd0; end
   always @(posedge sclk or posedge cs_n) begin
      if (cs_n) begin
         data_byte <= 8'd0;
         phase     <= 1'b0;
      end else begin
         phase <= ~phase;
         if (phase) data_byte <= data_byte + 8'd1;
      end
   end
   always @(negedge sclk or posedge cs_n) begin
      if (cs_n) q <= 4'd0;
      else      q <= phase ? data_byte[7:4] : data_byte[3:0];
   end
end else begin : g_one
   reg [2:0] phase;
   reg       q;
   initial begin phase = 3'd0; q = 1'b0; end
   always @(posedge sclk or posedge cs_n) begin
      if (cs_n) begin
         data_byte <= 8'd0;
         phase     <= 3'd0;
      end else begin
         phase <= phase + 3'd1;
         if (phase == 3'd7) data_byte <= data_byte + 8'd1;
      end
   end
   always @(negedge sclk or posedge cs_n) begin
      if (cs_n) q <= 1'b0;
      else      q <= data_byte[7 - phase];
   end
end endgenerate
@

Tri-state drivers. 4-lane drives all four IO pins from `q[3:0]`;
1-lane drives only `io[1]` (MISO) from `q[0]` and leaves the
other three lanes Hi-Z. Output enable is held high while CS is
low.

<<SPI streaming: io drivers>>=
wire oe = ~cs_n;
generate if (LANES == 4) begin : g_io_quad
   assign io[0] = oe ? g_quad.q[0] : 1'bz;
   assign io[1] = oe ? g_quad.q[1] : 1'bz;
   assign io[2] = oe ? g_quad.q[2] : 1'bz;
   assign io[3] = oe ? g_quad.q[3] : 1'bz;
end else begin : g_io_one
   assign io[0] = 1'bz;
   assign io[1] = oe ? g_one.q : 1'bz;
   assign io[2] = 1'bz;
   assign io[3] = 1'bz;
end endgenerate
@

